<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Equisetum</i> <i>arvense</i>, <i>Equisetum</i> ×<i>ferrissii</i> or <i>Equisetum</i> <i>hyemale</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Avena</i> <i>barbata</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>diandrus</i>, <i>Cynodon</i> <i>dactylon</i> or <i>Vulpia</i> <i>myuros</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 1.5 m; cover is intermittent to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Equisetum </i>spp. > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (Buck-Diaz et al. 2012).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Riparian areas, including streambanks, floodplains, edges of levees, seeps, ponds, and riparian forest openings. Soils are alluvial, may be seasonally and/or intermittently flooded. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Equisetum arvense </i>as FAC, <i>E. hyemale, E. laevigatum </i>and <i>E.  palustre </i>as FACW, and <i>E. telmateia </i>as OBL plants. </div>
</div>

        
