<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Equisetum </i> spp. are erect reed-like, perennial, rhizomatous herbs that can reach 3 ft (0.9 m) tall. Their evergreen stems are cylindrical, jointed, hollow, usually unbranched, and have rough longitudinal ridges. The tiny leaves are joined together around the stem, forming a narrow black-green band or sheath at each joint. Like other Pteridophytes (ferns and their relatives), horsetails do not produce flowers or seeds, but reproduce through spores. <i>Equisetum arvense </i> also produces sterile non-reproductive stems while <i>Equisetum hyemale </i> has only fertile spore-producing stems.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Equisetum variegatum </i> does not occur in California. <i>Equisetum arvense, E. hyemale </i>, and other <i>Equisetum </i>spp. are widespread throughout California except in the deserts and southern Great Valley. They often produces large colonies of green stems that persist through the winter. These plants are native to California but are considered to be potentially weedy or invasive according to some (Whitson, et al. 1996). The Jepson Manual recognizes <i>Equisetum hyemale </i> ssp. <i>affine </i> with <i>E. hyemale</i> var. <i>californicum</i> and <i>E. hyemale</i> var. <i>robustum</i> as synonyms.<br/>
<br/>
Species in the genus <i>Equisetum </i> concentrate silica in their tissue, so that pioneers found the stems suitable for scouring pots and pans. The genus <i>Equisetum </i>has been studied often as a means to understand the evolution of vascular plants. It is the single surviving genus of a class of land-dominating primitive vascular plants that dates back to the mid-Devonian period (350 + million years ago).<br/>
<br/>
Although we have little data on this alliance in California, the alliance occurs broadly in the western United States to Canada in wet meadows, streambanks, and ditches (NatureServe 2015). While one association is noted from the Great Valley (<i>Equisetum hyemale</i>), it is expected to be more common in California. More study is needed to understand this alliance in the state. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
