    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac-d, Af, Ah, Aj). Small stands observed throughout these subsections.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). Stands occur in riparian areas within the valley, including streambanks, floodplains, edges of levees, seeps, ponds, and riparian forest openings. Soils may be seasonally and/or intermittently flooded (Buck-Diaz et al. 2012). One stand of <i>Equisetum hyemale</i> observed on the egde of the levee along the Feather River (VegCAMP & GIC 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Da-b, Dh, Dl). Stands observed throughout these subsections.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Al). Stands expected, based on plant observations in the Consortium of California Herbaria (2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Eb, Ed-h, Ej-u). Stands observed throughout these subsections.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-d). Stands are probable throughout these subsections.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bd-e, Bg-h). Stands of <i>Equisetum arvense</i> and <i>Equisetum hyemale</i> have been observed along rivers and creeks in the San Gabriel and San Bernardino Moutains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Dl-m). Stands expected, based on plant observations in the Consortium of California Herbaria (2018).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands of this and related riparian types have continued impacts including human development, agriculture, transportation corridors, water usage, hydrologic modifications, and changes in climate/weather. </div>
</div>

    

    

